    "body": "### Description\n\nI'm getting the following behavior:\n\n1. I open up a ruby file in a ruby project that uses `ast-grep`.\n2. Ruby LSP starts as expected.\n3. I open a YAML file with the ruby file still open in the background.\n4. The Ruby LSP is now active on the YAML file and shows tons of syntax errors.\n\nWas super confused why this was happening so I dove into the code lol.\n\n#### Explanation and solution\n\n`ast-grep` and `ruby_lsp` both define their own `reuse_client` functions:\n\nhttps://github.com/neovim/nvim-lspconfig/blob/bf5abe69c1874531f359a822d0cff4d73e26113f/lsp/ruby_lsp.lua#L29-L32\n\nhttps://github.com/neovim/nvim-lspconfig/blob/bf5abe69c1874531f359a822d0cff4d73e26113f/lsp/ast_grep.lua#L15-L18\n\nBut they're missing a check comparing their name. Per the Neovim docs:\n\n> `{reuse_client}?` `(fun(client: vim.lsp.Client, config: vim.lsp.ClientConfig): boolean)` Predicate which decides if a client should be re-used. **Used on all running clients. The default implementation re-uses a client if name and root_dir matches.**\n\nNeither `ast-grep` or `ruby_lsp`'s `reuse_client` functions check that the client's name is the same as the config, despite both of their names being static. \n\nIn [`vim.lsp.start()`](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/33ea63011ca3c78b2a453dc6669ba5bf39147d9a/runtime/lua/vim/lsp.lua#L752-L763), all of the existing clients are iterated over, and the config's `reuse_client` is called on each. When I hit step 3 in my example, Ruby LSP is started already and `ast-grep` is hitting these lines (as `yaml` is a valid filetype for it). `ast-grep`'s `reuse_client` is called, and because the `cwd`s are the same, Ruby LSP is reused as the `ast-grep` language server.\n\nThe fix for this is simple, just adding a name check to each function:\n\n```lua\nreuse_client = function(client, config)\n    config.cmd_cwd = config.root_dir\n    return client.name == config.name and client.config.cmd_cwd == config.cmd_cwd\nend\n```\n\nThis fixes the issue and causes `ast-grep` to use a new client instead of reusing the wrong one.",
